## Extraction Pipeline

The core value of the platform is the **render-first extraction pipeline**. Every document — regardless of format, complexity, or content — goes through the same five-stage process.

```
DOCX / ODT uploaded
        │
        ▼
┌───────────────┐
│ LibreOffice   │  Converts DOCX/ODT → PDF.
│ headless      │  Renders fonts, OMML equations, embedded images,
│ (Stage 1)     │  and table formatting exactly as Word displays them.
└───────┬───────┘
        │
        ▼
┌───────────────┐
│ PyMuPDF       │  Renders each PDF page as a PNG at 200 DPI.
│ Page Renderer │  Produces pixel-perfect page images including
│ (Stage 2)     │  all diagrams, equations, and table layouts.
└───────┬───────┘
        │
        ▼
┌───────────────┐
│ Firebase      │  Each page PNG is uploaded to Firebase Storage.
│ Storage       │  Returns a tokenized download URL stored against
│ (Stage 3)     │  each question that has a visual element.
└───────┬───────┘
        │
        ▼
┌───────────────┐
│ Groq Vision   │  Each page image is sent to the vision model with
│ (Stage 4)     │  a subject-aware extraction prompt. Returns a
│               │  structured JSON array of question dicts including
│               │  LaTeX, markdown tables, and image URLs.
└───────┬───────┘
        │
        ▼
┌───────────────┐
│ Merge +       │  Questions from all pages are merged, deduplicated
│ Firestore     │  by question number, and written to Firestore in
│ (Stage 5)     │  batches of 400. Status updated to "extracted".
└───────────────┘
```

**Why render-first?** Parsing document internals (XML, ZIP blobs, namespace lookups) is fragile and format-specific. Rendering the document and using vision AI to read the result is the same approach a human takes — and handles every edge case: custom fonts, OMML equations, embedded images, merged table cells, and complex layouts.

---

## AI Provider Chain

Every AI call goes through a two-provider chain. If Groq fails for any reason — model deprecation, rate limit, timeout — Gemini is tried automatically. No manual intervention required.

```python
ai_text(prompt)
  │
  ├─▶ Groq (primary)
  │     Auto-resolves best available model from /models endpoint
  │     Invalidates model cache on decommission error
  │     Retries once on model-not-found errors
  │     │
  │     └─▶ Success → return response
  │         Failure → continue to fallback
  │
  └─▶ Gemini 2.0 Flash (fallback)
        Free tier: 1,500 requests/day, 1M token context
        │
        └─▶ Success → return response
            Failure → raise RuntimeError
```

**Groq model candidates** (tried in order, first available wins):
1. `llama-3.1-70b-versatile`
2. `llama3-70b-8192`
3. `llama-3.3-70b-specdec`
4. `llama-3.1-8b-instant` (last resort — reduced chunk size applies)

The resolved model is cached in memory for the process lifetime. When Groq deprecates a model mid-deployment, the next request automatically re-queries `/models` and resolves the next available candidate.

